  "answer": "No Sanskrit texts are present in the Falsafa corpus, so passages illustrating *prajna* (intuitive, transcendent wisdom) or *jnana* (direct, liberating knowledge) cannot be pulled. The corpus emphasizes translated philosophical/classical works, with a current focus on Old English heroic Christian poetry among its 37 titles.\n\nFor Old English *frod* (\"wise through age/experience/prudence, sage\") and *witig* (\"wise, knowing/prophetic, clever to the crowd\"), \"wisdom\" is a serviceable gloss in modern translations, capturing the shared sense of profound insight or sagacity. Representative passages:\n\n- **Frod**: In *Elene*, David is the \"frod fyrnweota, fæder Salomones\" (\"wise old seer, father of Solomon\"), invoked as an ancient authority on prophecy.[^1]\n- **Witig**: In *Andreas*, the animated stone shames the priests \"witig werede\" (\"wise to the crowd\"), speaking with prophetic authority despite being an inanimate \"frod fyrngeweorc\" (\"old wise work\").[^2]\n\n\"Wisdom\" creaks when *frod* emphasizes experiential age (\"wintrum frod\", \"old in winters\") vs. innate/divine *wit*, as when Andrew praises Christ (disguised as a young helmsman): \"You yourself are young... not old in winters, yet you have... wise understanding.\" Here, *wisdom* flattens the contrast between hoary prudence (*frod*) and precocious insight (*witig*-like), blurring heroic poetry's tension between worldly years and godly gift.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-624562).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-6406bd).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, ch. 1 [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-24dbdc).",
